{{refimprove|date=July 2014}} '''''Burns v Burns''''' [1984] [[Law Reports|Ch]] 317, [1984] 1 [[All England Law Reports|All ER]] 244) is a case in [[English property law]] dealing with the beneficial [[entitlement]]s of unmarried [[cohabitation|cohabittees]].
==Facts== The [[plaintiff]], Valerie Burns, lived with the [[defendant]] for 19 years, Patrick Burns, whom she never married. The house had been bought in the name of the defendant who also paid the purchase price with the plaintiff making no financial contributions to the purchase price or [[mortgage]] installments and had acted as a [[homemaker]] performing domestic duties.<ref>[http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/pntodd/cases/cases_b/burns.htm Full text of opinion] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118141141/http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/pntodd/cases/cases_b/burns.htm |date=November 18, 2007 }}</ref> She had however made financial contributions to the household with regards to household bills and redecorating.
==Judgment== The judgment of the case was that in the absence of a financial contribution which could be related to the acquisition to the property such as mortgage installments there is no right to a beneficial entitlement to a family home. This decision was affirmed by the [[Lord Justice of Appeal|Lords Justice]] [[Mark Waller (judge)|Waller]], [[Michael Fox (judge)|Fox]] and [[Anthony May (judge)|May]] in the [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}
==Notes== {{reflist|2}}
==References== *J Herring et al., ''[[Landmark Cases in Family Law]]'' (2011)
