[[File:Gwalia Stores and Moss-Vernon's Portrait Studio, St Fagans.jpg|250px|thumb|Gwalia Stores in its present location at St Fagans]] '''Gwalia Stores''' is a retail premises originally built at [[Ogmore Vale]], Glamorgan, in 1880 and currently located at [[St Fagans National History Museum]], [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]].<ref name="museum">[http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/en/stfagans/buildings/gwalia/ Historical Buildings – St Fagans: National History Museum – Gwalia Stores]. Accessed 14 November 2013</ref>
[[File:St Fagans National History Museum 85.JPG|thumb|left|The shop front of Gwalia Stores]] The stores were a family business, run by William Llewellyn and his family.<ref>[http://www.peoplescollection.org.uk/Collection/155-gwalia-stores-ogmore-vale People's Collection Wales: Gwalia Stores, Ogmore Vale]. Accessed 14 November 2013</ref> By 1916 the departments included bakery, ironmongery, grocery, men's outfitters, pharmacy and animal feeds. Some of the stores' employees also lodged on the premises.<ref name="museum"/> "Gwalia Stores" was a popular name for grocery stores in Wales during the early 20th century, and other shops with the same or similar names, unconnected to the one at St Fagans, can still be found.
The stores closed for business in Ogmore Vale in 1973 and reopened at St Fagans in 1991. Part of the shop is still a retail premises; the rest of the ground floor is set up as it would have been during the 1920s. The first floor contains a tearoom.
